<!-- ADR (Architecture Decision Record) Format.
     Each significant decision gets a unique DEC-N ID.

     ## When to write a DEC entry (granularity heuristics):
     WRITE a DEC when:
     - Choosing between 2+ viable alternatives (technology, pattern, architecture)
     - Making a trade-off that affects quality attributes (performance vs simplicity, etc.)
     - Constraining future options (database choice, API contract, protocol)
     - Deviating from established patterns or conventions
     - A decision would surprise a new team member reading the code
     DO NOT write a DEC for:
     - Implementation details with only one reasonable approach
     - Style/formatting choices covered by linters
     - Decisions already documented in requirements or design

     ## Status flow:
     Proposed → Accepted → (Deprecated | Superseded by DEC-N)
     - Proposed: Under discussion, not yet committed
     - Accepted: Committed and being implemented
     - Deprecated: No longer valid (explain why)
     - Superseded: Replaced by a newer decision (link to DEC-N)

     ## Reversibility scale:
     - High: Revert in minutes, no data migration (e.g., swap a utility function)
     - Medium: Revert in hours/days, migration or refactor needed (e.g., change DB schema)
     - Low: Revert is very costly or impractical (e.g., public API contract, data format on disk)
-->

<!-- example:
## DEC-1: [2026-03-16] SQLite vs PostgreSQL
<!-- confidence: 9 | source: user -- >
- **Status**: Accepted
- **Context**: Single-user local tool; operational simplicity preferred
- **Chosen**: SQLite (ncruces/go-sqlite3)
- **Alternatives**:
  - PostgreSQL: Full-featured but operational overhead
  - BoltDB: Simple but no FTS support
- **Rationale**: Single-user constraint makes PostgreSQL unnecessary. FTS5 covers search needs.
- **Evidence**: Benchmarked 10K record inserts — SQLite: 45ms, Bolt: 60ms, PG: 120ms (with network)
- **Consequences**: Multi-user would require migration
- **Related Decisions**: DEC-3 (FTS5 choice depends on SQLite)
- **Reversibility**: Medium (migration script needed)
- **Revisit When**: User count > 1 or concurrent write requirements emerge
-->

